Implement the GenServer `handle_call/3` callback for `OrderedLeaderboard`. It has
two clauses, both of which reply synchronously to the caller.

The **`:board`** clause answers a request for the caller-facing handle. Build a
board map `%{server: self(), entries: state.entries, index: state.index}` and
reply with `{:ok, board}`, leaving `state` unchanged.

The **`{:submit, player_id, score}`** clause serializes a score submission,
keeping only the player's all-time high and handing out the next sequence
number for deterministic tie-breaking. Read the current sequence from
`state.seq`, then look the player up in the secondary index (`state.index`):

- If the player has no existing entry, insert a fresh row with `insert_entry/4`
  (passing `state`, `player_id`, `score`, and the current `seq`), reply `:ok`,
  and advance the sequence by returning the state with `seq` incremented by 1.
- If the player already has an entry, recover their old score from the stored
  composite key `{old_neg, _old_seq, _old_pid}` (the old score is `-old_neg`).
  Only a strictly higher new score counts: when `score > old_score`, delete the
  old row from `state.entries` by its composite key, insert the new row with
  `insert_entry/4` at the current `seq`, reply `:ok`, and increment `seq`.
  Otherwise (a lower-or-equal score) it is a no-op: reply `:ok` and leave the
  state unchanged (do not consume a sequence number).

Both clauses use the `{:reply, reply, new_state}` GenServer form.

